M|rules|title: Use Explicit Conditional Rendering
M|rules|impact: LOW
M|rules|impactDescription: prevents rendering 0 or NaN
M|rules|tags: rendering, conditional, jsx, falsy-values
M|rules|Use explicit ternary operators (`? :`) instead of `&&` for conditional rendering when the condition can be `0`, `NaN`, or other falsy values that render.
M|rules|**Incorrect (renders "0" when count is 0):**
M|rules|```tsx
M|rules|function Badge({ count }: { count: number }) {
M|rules|return (
M|rules|<div>
M|rules|{count && <span className="badge">{count}</span>}
M|rules|</div>
M|rules|)
M|rules|}
M|rules|// When count = 0, renders: <div>0</div>
M|rules|// When count = 5, renders: <div><span class="badge">5</span></div>
M|rules|```
M|rules|**Correct (renders nothing when count is 0):**
M|rules|```tsx
M|rules|function Badge({ count }: { count: number }) {
M|rules|return (
M|rules|<div>
M|rules|{count > 0 ? <span className="badge">{count}</span> : null}
M|rules|</div>
M|rules|)
M|rules|}
M|rules|// When count = 0, renders: <div></div>
M|rules|// When count = 5, renders: <div><span class="badge">5</span></div>
M|rules|```